Unfortunately, it was not possible to make the patch smaller for these reasons:

An early (but wrong...) design decision was that only TestCaseElement can hold failure traces. I missed the fact that also TestSuites, TestDecorators, etc. can fail. The fix has to move various fields from TestCaseElement to the superclass TestElement to allow setting results there as well.

As a consequence, many signatures needed to be weakened to accept TestElements as well. Furthermore, calculation of the failure-state of TestSuiteElements became more complicated, since the suites' state now not only depend on the children's states, but also on the state of the suite itself.

Lastly, TestViewer needed a few fixes to accomodate for new updating requirements to show failed suites (+ a performance imporvement in processChangesInUI() and a horribly wron iteration in updateElementInTree()).
Approving the way this got fixed for 3.2 RC3 but it must be reviewed by a third party.

Review comments of the patch in attachment 40441:

A) TestRunSession::testFailed(): possible NPE

  Previously, an instanceof expression ensured a non-null TestCaseElement. Now that any TestElement can be tested, a null check should be added for the element retrieved from the fIdToTest map. If the element is null, an unexpected warning should be logged and returned, as was previously with non-TestCaseElements.


B) Status predicates

  This is would make some methods easier to understand, but is probably too much for this patch: similar to the existing Status::isFailure, one could imagine the following predicates:
  - isRunning() == RUNNING | RUNNING_FAILURE | RUNNING_ERROR
  - isError() == ERROR | RUNNING_ERROR
  - isFailure() == FAILURE | RUNNING_FAILURE 
  - isErrorOrFailure() == isError() | isFailure() [replaces current isFailure()]

The readability of the following methods would profit from these predicates:
  - TestSuiteElement::getStatus
  - RunnerViewHistory::getImageDescriptor
  - TestSessionLabelProvider::getImage

C) TestSuiteElement::getStatus:

Not sure about the status combination... and the interaction with getCombinedStatus (which is only used here - move?). Please explain. For example, what happens if the child state is RUNNING and the currently highest is RUNNING_ERROR?

D) TestRunnerViewPart::createControl

The initial value for the setShowFailuresOnly() call has changed - why?

Better patch

A) Sure, restored check (is null check now, not ! instanceof)

B/C) partly done in patch

D) We once discussed that disabling the filter should be the default. Was left in this patch by accident. Reverted change.
